National Director of Public Prosecutions Shaun Abrahams has handed in his representations to President Zuma, arguing why he should not be suspended. JOHANNESBURG - National Director of Public Prosecutions Shaun Abrahams has handed in his representations to President Jacob Zuma, arguing why he should not be suspended. Earlier this month the president wrote to Abrahams and prosecutors Sibongile Mzinyathi and Torie Pretorius, asking them to provide their reasons in the wake of their handling of the prosecution of Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan.The submissions will not be made public.The president wrote to them after civic rights groups Freedom Under Law and the Helen Suzman Foundation asked that the trio be suspended.Judge President Dunstan Mblambo said there was nothing to suggest that Zuma was not considering the suspension and kicked out the application with costs.Last week, the High Court in Pretoria dismissed an application brought by the groups. Judge President Dunstan Mlambo said there was nothing to suggest that Zuma was not considering the suspension and kicked out the application with costs.(Edited by Shimoney Regter